SIMPLE: hide
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hide
<hw>Hide</hw> <pr>(h⟦imac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Hid</conjf> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hidden</conjf> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧d"d'n)</pr>,
<conjf>Hid</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Hiding</conjf>
<pr>(h⟦imac⟧d"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hiden</ets>,
<ets>huden</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦ymac⟧dan</ets>; akin to Gr.
<grk>key`qein</grk>, and prob. to E. <ets>house</ets>, <ets>hut</ets>,
and perh. to E. <ets>hide</ets> of an animal, and to <ets>hoard</ets>.
Cf. <er>Hoard</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To conceal, or withdraw from
sight; to put out of view; to secrete.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A city that is set on an hill can not be <qex>hid</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. v. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If circumstances lead me, I will find⟦br⟧
Where truth is <qex>hid</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To withhold from knowledge; to keep secret; to
refrain from avowing or confessing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Heaven from all creatures <qex>hides</qex> the book of fate.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remove from danger; to shelter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the time of trouble he shall <qex>hide</qex> me in his
pavilion.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxvi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hide one's self</b></col>, <cd>to put one's self in a
condition to be safe; to secure protection.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧A prudent man
foreseeth the evil, and <xex>hideth himself</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Prov.
xxii. 3.</au> -- <col><b>To hide the face</b></col>, <cd>to withdraw
favor.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou didst <xex>hide thy face</xex>, and I was
troubled.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ps. xxx. 7.</au> -- <col><b>To hide the face
from</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To overlook; to pardon.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hide thy face from</xex> my sins.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ps. li. 9.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To withdraw favor from; to be displeased
with.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conceal; secrete; disguise; dissemble; screen;
cloak; mask; veil. See <er>Conceal</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hide</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hide
<hw>Hide</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To lie concealed; to keep one's
self out of view; to be withdrawn from sight or observation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bred to disguise, in public 'tis you <qex>hide</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hide and seek</b></col>, <cd>a play of children, in which
some hide themselves, and others seek them.</cd>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hide</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hide
<hw>Hide</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>h⟦imac⟧d</ets>, earlier
<ets>h⟦imac⟧ged</ets>; prob. orig., land enough to support a family; cf.
AS. <ets>h⟦imac⟧wan</ets>, <ets>h⟦imac⟧gan</ets>, members of a
household, and E. <ets>hind</ets> a peasant.]</ety> <fld>(O. Eng.
Law.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An abode or dwelling.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A measure of land, common in Domesday Book and old English
charters, the quantity of which is not well ascertained, but has been
differently estimated at 80, 100, and 120 acres.</def> <altsp>[Written
also <asp>hyde</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hide</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hide
<hw>Hide</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hide</ets>, <ets>hude</ets>,
AS. <ets>h⟦ymac⟧d</ets>; akin to D. <ets>huid</ets>, OHG.
<ets>h⟦umac⟧t</ets>, G. <ets>haut</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦umac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>,
Dan. & Sw. <ets>hud</ets>, L. <ets>cutis</ets>, Gr. <grk>ky`tos</grk>;
and cf. Gr. <grk>sky`tos</grk> skin, hide, L. <ets>scutum</ets> shield,
and E. <ets>sky</ets>. ⟦root⟧13.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The skin of an
animal, either raw or dressed; -- generally applied to the undressed
skins of the larger domestic animals, as oxen, horses, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The human skin; -- so called in contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O tiger's heart, wrapped in a woman's <qex>hide</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hide</ent>⟦br⟧

